{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"92f779db-ce4d-4aa4-8804-352e5054348c","content":"Here's a concise approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**5. Copy the trace off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Alternative — if `dotnet-trace` can't attach** (common in some container configs):\n\n- Use **environment variables** to enable EventPipe at startup:\n  ```\n  DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1\n  DOTNET_EventPipeOutputPath=C:\\trace.nettrace\n  ```\n  Restart the pod and the trace is written automatically.\n\n- Or use `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` for a quick live view of CPU, GC, and thread pool stats before committing to a full trace.\n\n**Tip:** If the global tool path isn't in `$PATH` inside the container, invoke it directly at `~/.dotnet/tools/dotnet-trace`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7e40bde4-4a0a-4a5f-8a85-0155196abc44","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":452},"id":"a7bcd9e5-8a93-4a76-b77e-79a526eca185","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:48:21.366Z","parentId":"f8c82372-4784-450c-9586-434c9de81a2e"}
